<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hicks and Matt Lait 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 MEN ONLY: Catholic bishops rarely disagree publicly with the Pope. And Bishop 
Norman F. McFarland of the Orange diocese wants it clear where he stands on 
Pope John Paul's latest decree against women priests. . . . The bishop has 
issued a news release stating: "I welcome this explicit reiteration of the 
constant 2,000-year teaching of the Church." He adds that it's an issue "about 
which some people have become confused or uncertain." 
</P>
<P>
 FED-EX THIS: You think Orange County is famous for Disneyland? The Angels? Its 
conservatives? When city of Orange police officers arrived last week in Quincy, 
in Northern California, to pick up murder suspect Edward Morgan, the sheriff's 
deputies there asked: "Where's the double-doubles?" Meaning In-N-Out Burgers, 
headquartered in Irvine. . . . To thank their northern counterparts, the local 
officers have made plans to deliver them 20 burgers from In-N-Out. No easy 
task: The closest available was in Modesto -- three hours away from Quincy. 
</P>
<P>
 HIS DAY: When American troops landed on the beaches of Normandy 50 years ago, 
Tom Moon of Orange was flying behind enemy lines in Burma for the OSS 
(forerunner of the CIA). Moon, who has written two books on the OSS, leaves 
Thursday, for a European speaking tour, sponsored partly by the U.S. Army. His 
six speeches one the war include one at Normandy on D-day, June 6. Says Moon: 
"I know that it's going to be greatly moving: What happened there was a 
slaughter." 
</P>
<P>
 TRUCKING ALONG: In tough times, some cities will do almost anything to make a 
buck -- even close off part of a very busy Harbor Boulevard. . . . Fullerton 
will close off one northbound lane of Harbor between Santa Fe and Wilshire 
avenues for most of today. Reason: A film crew is shooting a truck commercial. 
"The city views this as economic development," says spokeswoman Sylvia Mudrick. 
The film company had to pay $55 for a local business license, pay for the 
traffic officers, and is also spending a few bucks around town. 
</P>
