<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; CITY 
COUNCIL OKS 50% CUT IN TRASH SURCHARGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Los Angeles City Council has approved a 50% cut in the surcharge residents 
pay for automated refuse collection containers.  
</P>
<P>
 Effective July 1, homeowners will pay an extra $1.50 on top of the regular $3 
monthly sanitation equipment charge.For apartment dwellers, the total monthly 
fee will fall to $3, with the surcharge reduced to $1.  
</P>
<P>
 The council levied the extra fee two years ago to balance the budget. The 
surcharge is scheduled to expire June 30, 1995. 
</P>
<P>
 The reduction reflected the council's desire to give businesses and residents 
a break on taxes. The council also approved a cut in the 7.5% business tax 
surcharge.  
</P>
<P>
 Mayor Richard Riordan proposed eliminating the entire business tax surcharge 
as a gesture to soften the city's anti-business image. But the council wanted 
residents to get relief too, and halved the sanitation equipment surcharge as a 
compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
