<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: PLACENTIA/YORBA LINDA; SCHOOL COMPUTER PLANS UNVEILED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Placentia-Yorba Linda Unified School District officials this week unveiled an 
ambitious four-year plan to beef up technology in each of the district's 28 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
 The plan, which has not been approved by the Board of Trustees, is expected to 
cost $508,856. Most of that money will be spent on creating business computer 
labs at high schools and middle schools. 
</P>
<P>
 According to Supt. James O. Fleming, the project will be funded by several 
sources of "onetime money," primarily interest income earned on investments. 
</P>
<P>
 If approved, eight elementary schools will receive computers from the 
district's high schools and middle schools, which will receive new computers 
and equipment to build business labs. 
</P>
<P>
 According to a report prepared by Assistant Supt. Sharon McHolland, several 
teachers and other district employees, the objective is for each elementary 
school to have at least one 36-station computer lab. Some elementary schools 
already have such a lab, while others have obsolete equipment or fewer than 36 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
 The proposed plan also calls for each middle school and high school to have a 
business lab with software commonly used in the business world. The labs will 
be equipped so that students can use various "information networks" and 
"computer bulletin boards."  
</P>
<P>
 "The purpose is to empower all students to become contributing and employable 
members of society," the report states. 
</P>
<P>
 The plan calls for all the computers to be transferred or purchased and 
installed this summer. 
</P>
<P>
 Schools scheduled to get new equipment are Van Buren Elementary School, Yorba 
Linda Middle School, Bernardo Yorba Junior High, El Dorado High School, 
Valencia High School, Esperanza High School and El Camino Real Continuation 
School. 
</P>
<P>
 Golden Avenue, Glenknoll, Sierra Vista, Wagner, Morse Avenue, Glenview, 
Fairmont and Woodsboro elementary schools will receive equipment from the 
schools receiving new computers. 
</P>
<P>
 In the second through fourth years of the proposed plan, bar-coding technology 
will be installed in all school libraries and computers and software used by 
school secretaries will be upgraded. DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
</P>
</TEXT>
