<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: FULLERTON; INTERSECTION SAFETY PETITION CIRCULATED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Stacey Smith is tired of seeing people get hit and cars collide on the busy 
street corner outside her apartment. 
</P>
<P>
 So Smith and her neighbors have started a petition drive, soliciting 
signatures from people who live near the intersection of Commonwealth Avenue 
and State College Boulevard. They are gathering names on the street corner and 
plan to take the list to City Hall in an effort to ask city officials to make 
the intersection safer. 
</P>
<P>
 Even though the intersection has a traffic light and a crossing guard helps 
children get across in the mornings and after school, residents claim the 
intersection is still dangerous. They said they want left-turn-arrow signals 
installed to cut down on accidents. 
</P>
<P>
 "I get to hear the squealing of the tires, the crashing of the glass and the 
crunching of the metal from speeding cars, and I've called 911 many times," 
said Smith, 37. "It really makes me nervous and scared. If this problem doesn't 
get immediate attention, someone is going to get killed." 
</P>
<P>
 Smith said she is afraid to let her 6-year-old daughter, Marcie Treadwell, 
cross the intersection alone. She said she walks Marcie to Commonwealth 
Elementary School. 
</P>
<P>
 "When you're a pedestrian, drivers don't think about how it is to walk across 
the street. They're always in such a hurry that they tend to go faster without 
regard to the kids walking in front of them," Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
 Police have reported four accidents at the Commonwealth and State College 
intersection since January, city officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Smith's husband, Walter Treadwell, said he's been a witness to some of those 
accidents. "The intersection is an ongoing problem," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Smith and Treadwell said they have already collected about 50 signatures on 
their petitions and plan to collect several hundred more before presenting them 
to the City Council next month. 
</P>
<P>
 Usually, when residents make requests for traffic signals, the requests are 
studied by the Traffic Department and the city's Transportation Committee, 
officials said. MIMI KO 
</P>
</TEXT>
