<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SANTA ANA; ALTERNATIVE SITE FOR 'SPACE SAVER' URGED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEE ROMNEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Santa Ana schools trustee Rosemarie Avila has sent an open letter to her 
fellow board members, urging them to choose another site for a controversial 
"space-saver" school now slated to be built at a shopping center here.  
</P>
<P>
 "I am requesting that we move quickly to submit another space-saver project in 
case this one is denied by the state," Avila said in her letter, dated Monday.  
</P>
<P>
 "This space-saver concept offers us a great opportunity to receive priority 
funding. We must act immediately to be first in line again should we lose the 
Marketplace site." 
</P>
<P>
 The school might be funded under a novel state program designed to build 
schools in congested urban areas without condemning homes or businesses.  
</P>
<P>
 But the issue of the school has sharply divided the board, as well as the City 
Council and residents who live near the proposed site. 
</P>
<P>
 In February, the school board majority voted to approve the Bristol 
Marketplace site at Bristol and 17th streets. The school district had already 
sent a preliminary appraisal for the site to state officials, who set nearly 
$23 million aside for the project.  
</P>
<P>
 Since then, the shopping center property has come under fire from some local 
residents and officials who said the Santa Ana Unified School District didn't 
give adequate consideration to cheaper sites.  
</P>
<P>
 State officials also have criticized the steep preliminary appraisal for 
including the cost to tear down and rebuild two buildings at the mall. 
</P>
<P>
 The State Allocation Board will vote next month on whether to proceed or 
revoke Santa Ana's funding altogether. 
</P>
<P>
 In her letter, Avila said the parents of Santa Ana have been placed on "a 
roller-coaster ride" as the site has been debated. She urged that some 
boarded-up apartments on a 12-acre property valued at $6.9 million be 
considered instead. 
</P>
<P>
 But other board members and district officials have criticized that property 
as untenable. The blighted apartments are tied up in litigation and would have 
to be annexed from the Orange School District.LEE ROMNEY 
</P>
