<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA / ANTELOPE VALLEY; COPTER PATROL CITES TRESPASSING JOY RIDER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK SABBATINI, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Brian Gruhlke was trying to get his pickup truck unstuck from a desolate field 
just after midnight Monday when a blinding light suddenly focused on him from 
out of the sky. 
</P>
<P>
 Nearer and nearer it came until it landed in the field nearby. 
</P>
<P>
 But this was no close encounter. It was a sheriff's deputy in a helicopter who 
gave him a ticket for trespassing on the field. 
</P>
<P>
 "Actually, I was a little bit surprised," Gruhlke said.  
</P>
<P>
 Gruhlke, 20, who lives in Valencia and works at a Pizza Hut, said he had taken 
a friend for a joy ridethrough a large field at the east end of Rye Canyon 
Road, near the site of the new Valencia High School. 
</P>
<P>
 But after making a partial circle around the field, the 1988 Toyota pickup 
sunk into the dirt. 
</P>
<P>
 Deputy Mark Cohen, an observation deputy for the helicopter at the Santa 
Clarita Valley Sheriff's Station, spotted the truck at about 12:30 a.m. Tuesday 
and asked pilot David L'Hureux to land. Cohen said he was worried that the 
plowed field, owned by the Newhall Land and Farming Co., might be planted with 
seeds. 
</P>
<P>
 Cohen disembarked from the helicopter and asked Gruhlke if he needed help with 
the truck. Gruhlke said no, and then Cohen gave him a misdemeanor citation for 
trespassing. 
</P>
<P>
 Gruhlke said he did not know the field was privately owned. 
</P>
<P>
 Cohen said the station's helicopter is used primarily for emergencies and to 
patrol remote areas of the Santa Clarita and Antelope valleys. But it has been 
useful for spotting people driving illegally in off-road areas, he said, and 
for spotting people getting too close to flooded rivers following a storm or 
acting suspiciously in areas where brush fires could be set. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're out there not to give these people tickets because we like to, but 
because we're trying to prevent stuff," Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
 Gruhlke isn't sure all that extra effort is worthwhile. 
</P>
<P>
 "It seems to me that they have nothing better to do than harass young people, 
when there's (more serious crimes) going on in other parts," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
