<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Debora Vrana, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Foreclosures Go Up: Orange County housing foreclosures jumped 11.1% during the 
first four months of this year compared to the same period last year, according 
to Dataquick Information Systems. 
</P>
<P>
 An estimated 3,108 homes in Orange County were foreclosed on during that time, 
compared to 2,797 homes the previous year, Dataquick said.The Southern 
California region had an 8% increase in foreclosures during the first four 
months, while Los Angeles County showed a 6.8% increase. 
</P>
<P>
 "Foreclosure activity is a so-called lagging indicator and what we're seeing 
here is year-old distress. Most lenders try to work things out with their 
borrowers and wait as long as they can before they start the formal foreclosure 
process," said Donald L. Cohn, chief executive of Dataquick in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
 The state's foreclosure problem is still most severe in Southern California, 
Dataquick found, especially in Riverside, San Bernardino, Orange and Los 
Angeles counties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
