<HEADLINE>
<P>
RENO AIR IS CLOSER TO CHALLENGING SOUTHWEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WOODYARD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A week after Southwest Airlines ushered in a new era of lower fares at John 
Wayne Airport, another low-cost, no-frills carrier is poised on the runway. 
</P>
<P>
 Reno Air, an upstart Nevada-based airline that has grown quickly since 1992, 
wants to operate an unspecified number of American Airline's flight slots from 
the Orange County airport. 
</P>
<P>
 Although Reno Air has been denied access to the airport in the past because 
not enough landing slots were available, the joint operation plan with American 
has won the blessings of Airport Director Jan Mittermeier. 
</P>
<P>
 "The county does wish to encourage broad-based competitive air service," 
Mittermeier wrote in a letter to the airline's lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
 Mittermeier, who is asking the Airport Commission to approve the cooperative 
operating deal at its meeting tonight, said she approves only with a hefty set 
of restrictions, such as limiting Reno Air to six daily round-trip flights. She 
also wants to try out the joint operation through September. 
</P>
<P>
 The joint arrangement could benefit both airlines. Reno Air would feed 
passengers into American's profitable long-range flights. In return, Reno Air 
would benefit from its existing program of crediting its passengers through 
American Airlines' frequent-flier program. 
</P>
<P>
 Reno Air has not outlined how many flights or what destinations it has in 
mind. The airline flies to various cities in the West, including Los Angeles 
International Airport. A Reno Air spokesman offered no substantive comment on 
the airline's plans, and American Airlines officials could not be reached for 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
 But commission documents indicate that Reno Air plans to fly some or all of 
American's flights from Orange County to San Jose. Reno Air, with its low-cost 
structure and one-way fares of $72 to San Jose, would have a better chance of 
competing against Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
 Southwest started flying eight round trips daily to San Jose and seven daily 
to Oakland with an everyday fare of $69 each way. American was charging up to 
$140 one way on the San Jose flights. It has since matched Southwest's fare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
